member.remarks:
Depending on what a caller provides as search criteria, the following logic applies:

A) In case custom properties are provided (SIPLACEProPath, SIPLACEProObjectType, SIPLACEProOID_Long or any other
content in the CustomProperties collection):

1. Define the filter: 

1A) CustomProperties is filled: This will be taken as filter.

1B) Otherwise SIPLACEPro... properties are taken as filter.

2. Get all Services that match the rest of the SearchCriteria (ServiceName, ServiceVersion, Product, Grouped, Endpoint)


3. Get all Factory Layout objects that match the custom properties filter.

4. If there are Services from step 2 that are assigned to the found FactoryLayout objects of step 3 then return those.


5. If not, traverse up one level from all Factory Layout objects and repeat step 4.

6. If the enterprise level is reached without finding a match, return the list of step 2 by filtering for un-configured
services ONLY if ServiceMatchCriteria.DoNotReturnDefaultServices is false.

In case it is true, an empty collection is returned.



B) In case no custom properties are provided, the following logic applies:

1. Get all services that match the rest of the SearchCriteria (ServiceName, ServiceVersion, Product, Grouped, Endpoint)
and return those.



Case A: Sample code for finding the right service or services for one SIPLACE Pro line (which is represented as a WorkCell in the factory layout):

(This finds the name based line)

    ServiceLocatorClient client = new ServiceLocatorClient();
    ServiceMatchCriteria match = new ServiceMatchCriteria();
    match.ServiceName = "Service Name";
    match.SiplaceObjectType = "Line";
    match.SIPLACEProPath = "SIPLACE Pro Line1";
    match.SIPLACEProDBId = guid; // this is optional if only one database is used in a factory
    List<ServiceDescription> services = client.FindServices(match);



Case A: Alternatively, one can search based on OID and Database ID:


    ServiceLocatorClient client = new ServiceLocatorClient();
    ServiceMatchCriteria match = new ServiceMatchCriteria();
    match.ServiceName = "Service Name";
    match.SIPLACEProOID_Long = 1704;  // the property SIPLACEProOID is obsolete, please use SIPLACEProOID_Long instead
    match.SIPLACEProDBId = guid; // this is optional if only one database is used in a factory
    List<ServiceDescription> services = client.FindServices(match);



Case B: This shows how to just search upwards beginning with a certain factory layout object:


    ServiceLocatorClient client = new ServiceLocatorClient();
    ServiceMatchCriteria match = new ServiceMatchCriteria();
    match.ServiceName = "Service Name";
    match.SIPLACEProOID_Long = 1704;  // the property SIPLACEProOID is obsolete, please use SIPLACEProOID_Long instead
    match.SIPLACEProDBId = guid; // this is optional if only one database is used in a factory
    List<ServiceDescription> services = client.FindServices(match);

